mportance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n2161,\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"The rolling budget prepared for Timana Co for the next four quarters, including detailed revenue, direct labour, direct material, contribution, fixed production overhead, administration costs, and profit projections.\"\"\",14\n2061,\"\"\"ADMINISTRATION COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Administration costs\"\" are the expenses related to the general administration and operation of the business. These costs include salaries of administrative staff, office supplies, and rent. Additionally, administration costs will increase by $37,500 every quarter, starting from Q2, due to the employment of a change manager with an annual salary of $150,000. A 3% increase in administration costs has already been adjusted in the figures provided.\",3\n1565,\"\"\"DIRECT LABOUR\"\"\",\"\"\"Direct labour\"\" refers to the wages and salaries of employees that can be directly attributed to the production of specific goods or services. It is a variable cost that increases by 3% every quarter to reflect the increase in sales volume. Additionally, in Q3, there is a one-off increase of $5,000 to account for training costs.\",3\n468,\"\"\"PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Profit\"\" is the financial gain realized when the amount of revenue gained exceeds the expenses, costs, and taxes involved in sustaining the activity. It is obtained when the revenue from sales surpasses the total costs of production.\",3\n2153,\"\"\"DIRECT MATERIAL\"\"\",\"\"\"DIRECT MATERIAL\"\" refers to the raw materials and components that are directly used in the manufacturing of a product. It is considered a variable cost that increases by 3% every quarter to reflect the increase in sales volume.\",2\n2157,\"\"\"ADMINISTRATION COSTS ASSUMPTION\"\"\",\"\"\"The assumption that administration costs would increase by 3% in Q3 to account for an increase in the rent for the building.\"\"\",1\n2160,\"\"\"CHANGE MANAGER\"\"\",\"\"\"The new position created for a 'change manager' with an annual salary of $150,000 starting at the beginning of Q2, affecting the administration cost.\"\"\",1\n2156,\"\"\"FIXED PRODUCTION OVERHEADS ASSUMPTION\"\"\",\"\"\"The assumption that fixed production overheads would increase by $10,000 from Q3 onwards due to extra maintenance.\"\"\",1\n2159,\"\"\"PRODUCTION MANAGER'S COMMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The production manager's comment that the direct labour cost was higher due to an increase in the minimum wage and that there will be a one-off increase of $5,000 in Q3 for additional training required under health and safety legislation.\"\"\",1\n2154,\"\"\"SALES VOLUME GROWTH ASSUMPTION\"\"\",\"\"\"The assumption that sales volume would grow at the same fixed compound rate every quarter.\"\"\",1\n2155,\"\"\"VARIABLE COSTS ASSUMPTION\"\"\",\"\"\"The assumption that direct material and direct labour are wholly variable costs.\"\"\",1\n2158,\"\"\"SALES MANAGER'S COMMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The sales manager's comment that he had to reduce selling prices to boost demand as the market became more competitive.\"\"\",1\n2163,\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET APPROACH\"\"\",\"\"\"A rolling budget approach involves continuously updating the budget to reflect changes in the business environment. This approach requires frequent updates and adjustments to the budget, which can be facilitated by training programs and integrated information systems.\"\"\",8\n1560,\"\"\"TRANSFER PRICE PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Transfer price per unit = Total cost / (1 - Profit margin percentage)\"\"\",6\n2162,\"\"\"FIXED PRODUCTION OVERHEAD\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed production overhead costs will remain at $120,000 in Q2 and increase to $130,000 in Q3 onwards.\"\"\",1\n2165,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MEASURES\"\"\",\"\"\"Performance measures should be adjusted to reflect the new rolling budget system. This includes setting realistic targets that reflect the current economic environment and spreading targets more evenly throughout the year to improve staff motivation.\"\"\",1\n2164,\"\"\"TRAINING PROGRAMS\"\"\",\"\"\"Training programs for sales managers and finance staff are essential to ensure the smooth implementation of the rolling budget approach. These programs will improve their knowledge and reduce resistance to change.\"\"\",1\n2166,\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET IMPLEMENTATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Rolling budget implementation should involve staff consultation, cost-benefit analysis, and measures to avoid disruption to productivity or morale.\"\"\",1\n451,\"\"\"TOTAL COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Total costs are the sum of fixed and variable costs incurred by a business in the production of goods or services. It is a crucial factor in determining profitability.\"\"\",3\n160,\"\"\"TOTAL COST FOR EACH PRODUCT USING TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Total cost for each product using traditional absorption costing is calculated by adding direct material cost, direct labor cost, and fixed overhead cost based on machine hours. For example, for Product A, the total cost is $82, and for Product B, it is $116.\"\"\",5\n162,\"\"\"COMPARISON OF COSTS UNDER ABC AND ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"The comparison of costs under ABC and absorption costing shows significant differences in the cost per unit for products. For Product A, the cost increases by 26% under ABC, while for Product B, the cost decreases by 3%. The main reason for the difference is the allocation of set-up costs, which are more accurately reflected in the ABC system.\"\"\",3\n161,\"\"\"TOTAL COST FOR EACH PRODUCT USING ABC SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Total cost for each product using the ABC system is calculated by adding direct material cost, direct labor cost, and overhead costs traced to products based on multiple cost drivers. For example, for Product A, the total cost is $103.67, and for Product B, it is $112.75.\"\"\",5\n159,\"\"\"QUIZ: ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING V ABSORPTION COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz compares the total cost for each product using traditional absorption costing and the ABC system. It involves calculating the cost per unit for products A and B under both costing methods and identifying the main reasons for the differences.\"\"\",3\n165,\"\"\"DIRECT LABOR COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Direct labor cost refers to the wages and salaries of employees who are directly involved in the production of a product. This cost is included in the total cost calculation in both traditional absorption costing and the ABC system.\"\"\",2\n164,\"\"\"DIRECT MATERIAL COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Direct material cost refers to the cost of raw materials that are directly used in the production of a product. This cost is a part of the total cost calculation in both traditional absorption costing and the ABC system.\"\"\",2\n166,\"\"\"FIXED OVERHEAD COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed overhead cost\"\" refers to the indirect costs that do not vary with the level of production. These costs include rent, utilities, salaries of administrative staff, and insurance. In traditional absorption costing, fixed overhead costs are allocated based on a single cost driver, such as machine hours.\",2\n1562,\"\"\"MINIMUM TRANSFER PRICE FOR DIVISION A\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the minimum transfer price that Division A would accept for transferring Product S to Division B, considering external demand and opportunity costs.\"\"\",1\n1559,\"\"\"OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"Overheads are the ongoing expenses of operating a business that are not directly attributed to specific business activities. They can be fixed or variable.\"\"\",1\n1561,\"\"\"TRANSFER PRICING OBJECTIVES\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz tests the understanding of the bases for setting a transfer price that results in goal congruent behavior by both the selling and receiving divisions.\"\"\",1\n1563,\"\"\"TRANSFER PRICING POLICY\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz evaluates the objectives of a good transfer pricing system and whether a given transfer pricing policy achieves those objectives.\"\"\",1\n167,\"\"\"MULTIPLE COST DRIVERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Multiple cost drivers refer to the various factors that cause overhead costs to be incurred, such as machine setups, production runs, and quality inspections. In the ABC approach, overhead costs are allocated based on these multiple cost drivers.\"\"\",1\n1342,\"\"\"TOTAL PRODUCT COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Total product cost = Direct material + Direct labour + Variable overhead + Fixed overhead cost\"\"\",2\n2062,\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COST PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Life cycle cost per unit = Total costs / Number of units produced over the life cycle\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n331,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Revenue is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",27\n445,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Contribution is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",21\n1831,\"\"\"ADMINISTRATION COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Administration costs are a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",17\n1479,\"\"\"DIRECT LABOUR\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Direct labour is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",17\n490,\"\"\"PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Profit is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",17\n233,\"\"\"FIXED PRODUCTION OVERHEADS\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed production overheads are a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",17\n1854,\"\"\"DIRECT MATERIAL\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Direct material is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",16\n1859,\"\"\"ADMINISTRATION COSTS ASSUMPTION\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"The rolling budget for the next four quarters i